### Operator Overloading in C#

Operator overloading allows custom types to define how standard operators (+, -, *, etc.) work with them.

### Declaring Operator Overloads

```csharp
public struct Vector2
{
    public double X { get; }
    public double Y { get; }

    public Vector2(double x, double y) => (X, Y) = (x, y);

    // Binary operator
    public static Vector2 operator +(Vector2 a, Vector2 b)
        => new Vector2(a.X + b.X, a.Y + b.Y);

    public static Vector2 operator -(Vector2 a, Vector2 b)
        => new Vector2(a.X - b.X, a.Y - b.Y);

    // Unary operator
    public static Vector2 operator -(Vector2 v)
        => new Vector2(-v.X, -v.Y);

    // Scalar multiplication
    public static Vector2 operator *(Vector2 v, double scalar)
        => new Vector2(v.X * scalar, v.Y * scalar);

    // Equality operators (should also override Equals and GetHashCode)
    public static bool operator ==(Vector2 a, Vector2 b)
        => a.X == b.X && a.Y == b.Y;

    public static bool operator !=(Vector2 a, Vector2 b)
        => !(a == b);
}
```

### Usage

```csharp
var v1 = new Vector2(1, 2);
var v2 = new Vector2(3, 4);

var sum = v1 + v2;       // (4, 6)
var diff = v2 - v1;      // (2, 2)
var neg = -v1;           // (-1, -2)
var scaled = v1 * 5;     // (5, 10)
bool equal = v1 == v2;   // false
```

### Overloadable Operators

| Category | Operators |
|----------|-----------|
| Arithmetic | `+`, `-`, `*`, `/`, `%` |
| Comparison | `==`, `!=`, `<`, `>`, `<=`, `>=` |
| Unary | `+`, `-`, `!`, `~`, `++`, `--` |
| Bitwise | `&`, `|`, `^`, `<<`, `>>` |
| Conversion | `implicit`, `explicit` |

### Non-Overloadable Operators

| Operator | Reason |
|----------|--------|
| `=` | Assignment |
| `?.` | Null-conditional |
| `?:` | Ternary conditional |
| `??` | Null-coalescing |
| `&&`, `||` | Short-circuit logical |
| `[]` | Indexer (use indexers) |
| `()` | Invocation |
| `.` | Member access |

### Conversion Operators

```csharp
public struct Fraction
{
    public int Numerator { get; }
    public int Denominator { get; }

    public Fraction(int num, int den)
    {
        Numerator = num;
        Denominator = den;
    }

    // Implicit conversion from int to Fraction
    public static implicit operator Fraction(int value)
        => new Fraction(value, 1);

    // Explicit conversion from Fraction to double
    public static explicit operator double(Fraction f)
        => (double)f.Numerator / f.Denominator;
}

// Usage
Fraction f = 5;             // implicit int -> Fraction
double d = (double)f;       // explicit Fraction -> double
```

### Rules for Operator Overloading

| Rule | Description |
|------|-------------|
| Must be public static | `public static ReturnType operator ...` |
| At least one operand | Must be the containing type |
| Symmetry | Overload both `==` and `!=` |
| Consistency | If `==` is overloaded, also override `Equals()` and `GetHashCode()` |

> **Key Point:** Operator overloading makes custom types feel like built-in types. Use it when the operator's meaning is obvious and intuitive. Always maintain symmetry: overload `==` with `!=`, `<` with `>`, etc. Override `Equals()` and `GetHashCode()` when overloading `==`.

### Comparison Operators

```csharp
public static bool operator <(Vector2 a, Vector2 b)
    => a.Length() < b.Length();
public static bool operator >(Vector2 a, Vector2 b)
    => a.Length() > b.Length();
```

### Increment/Decrement

```csharp
public static Vector2 operator ++(Vector2 v)
    => new Vector2(v.X + 1, v.Y + 1);
```

